<font color="#FF0000">A WISER PERSPECTIVE NEEDED</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  3 23:49:01 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
<br>
It was the philosopher George <br>
Santayana who said that those who do <br>
not remember the lessons of history <br>
are condemned to repeat them.  <br>
Obviously this is is all too relevant <br>
to the Vietnam experience.  I would <br>
think then that two crucial lessons <br>
should have emerged from that.         <br>
First, anyone considering whether or <br>
not to partipate in war must of <br>
necessity consider the consequences of <br>
that action.  He should even step back <br>
and wonder why he is now in the <br>
position of having to make such a <br>
critical decision.  Those with a <br>
Buddhist perspective will instantly <br>
recognize this as the Law of Karma but <br>
notwithstanding that, the implications <br>
of this sort of decision where <br>
inevitable suffering is at stake is <br>
simply too important to be taken <br>
lightly.                               <br>
Secondly, unless we overcome the <br>
habitual tendency to think in <br>
dualistic fashion(the outside enemy <br>
vs. the noble us)it is all too <br>
possible to discover new adversaries <br>
who will not pose any grave threat to <br>
our safety.  The solution doesn't <br>
necessarily lie in believing that the <br>
entire &quot;outside&quot; world is our friend <br>
but that we should take the time to <br>
investigate what we believe is a <br>
threat to find out if it is indeed so. <br>
With Vietnam, for instance, we would <br>
have learned of their long standing <br>
antagonism towards the Chinese and we  <br>
could have assisted them(both North &amp; <br>
South) in being self-sufficient enough <br>
to repudiate assistance from China and <br>
perhaps the U.S.S.R. as well.          <br>

